title: For Sale/Trade:  Springfield 1903 M1
postcontent: This listing is for a Springfield 1903 Mark1 bolt-action rifle.  The firearm is about 80% to 85% condition (very nice for something of this age).  Much of the bluing is still seen on the metal.  There is some small pitting in the metal in a few places (again, to be expected with this age).  This rifle was most likely used during WW1 and WW2 by those in service.I have removed the last two digits from the serial number in the photos.  The serial number is 5511XX.  Some argue the lower numbered serial numbers (those below 800,000) are not as durable as the models above 800,000 (in terms of heat treatment on the barrel).  The way I see it, this rifle made it through two world wars, and hundreds of rounds of ammo in my backyard.  To me, a lower serial number only makes an antique firearm that much more appealing.The barrel is stamped with U.S.M.C, and the numbers "1 - 44".  It also has a small encircled letter S under the numbers.  This suggests the barrel was replaced at some time (by Sedgley), and was produced in January of 1944.  It is entirely possible this rifle was custom built for a United States Marine Corp member, but I have yet to find definitive proof (would love to hear your comments).Rifle is chambered in 30-06.  It holds five rounds in the loader.  Bolt action can be switched to pull rounds directly from the loader (until empty); or to lock back after each discharge, allowing rounds to be dropped in by hand, one at a time.  All moving parts are clean, reliable and fully functional.  Trigger and bolt assembly were fully disassembled and oiled (February 22, 2017).  The feed ramp is clean and free of any defects.  The barrel rifling is in excellent condition.Please email with any questions.  I will respond to all reasonable offers.

The goal of this cooperation was to develop and produce a highly accurate semi-automatic rifle with excellent shooting performance that is suitable for the dynamic disciplines as well as semi-auto precision shooting. The MSR RX22 offers an extremely accurate self-loading rifle platform with excellent shooting performance and exceptional reliability. This new Anschütz rifle operates on a force-locking blowback action system with a hammer lock.
The MSR RX22 barrels are manufactured to the same exacting tolerances of Anschütz' target barrels with a special button-rifling process. The barrel also features a recessed target crown. The single-stage trigger's components are hardened and finely ground to produce a fast trigger with a very consistent release. The trigger can be adjusted from 3.3 to 5.5 pounds, and it is set at 4 pounds by the factory.
The MSR RX22 was designed for ease of use for either a left- or right-handed shooter. The cocking handle can be located in any of three positions on either side of the rifle for a total of six possible cocking-handle locations. The trigger-locking safety is easily engaged by way of a large selector switch on either side of the rifle.
The MSR RX22 is available in four versions. The Desert and Black Hawk models feature a side-folding stock that is collapsible for length of pull and adjustable for cheek weld. Both rifles have Picatinny rails on the side and bottom of the foreend for attaching accessories. The Precision and Precision Black models have fixed wooden stocks and foreend components. All rifles have a full-length Picatinny rail on top for mounting the included flip-up iron sights as well as your choice of optics.
The rifles come equipped with one 10-round polymer detachable single-stack magazine, and magazines with capacities of 2, 5, 20 and 22 rounds are also available as accessory items.Has flip up sights and a case. title: For Sale:  Israeli K98 Mauser 7.62x51 w/ Waffenamts
postcontent: K98 Israeli Mauser – Mix of Czech and German parts. Built by Mauser for the German Army in 1945, near the end of WWII. It was accepted by the Germans and stamped with at least 4 Waffenamts. After the war it was sent to Czechoslovakia and had a post war stock put on it (as indicated by the finger grips). Around 1947 it was sold to the Israeli’s and the Star of David was stamped on it. Most German K98’s received by the Israeli’s had the Waffenamts ground off. However, this rifle has at least 4 remaining Waffenamts (see pictures). In 1957 it was rebarreled to 7.62. The barrel and stock was stamped with “7.62”. Eventually this rifle was sold to Ecuador and later imported to the United States by Century Arms (small import stamp on barrel – see pictures). Beginning in 1968, firearms imported into the United States had to have an import stamp. It is plausible that this rifle was used during the Six Day War in June 1967 between Israel and Egypt, Jordan and Syria. Of course there is no way to prove this, but circumstantial evidence suggests it. Rifle comes with genuine, period correct Israeli sling and Israeli bayonet. The bayonet was designed for the K98 but is not original to this particular rifle. The bayonet does not fit very well on this rifle, but I’ve never tried to force it on. It’s been a safe queen for as long as I’ve owned it. Due to its rich history, I’ve never tried to shoot it. I know everyone says their rifle is rare, but this one genuinely is. There are not many Israeli Mausers in the market and very few Israeli K98 Mausers still has Waffenamts remaining on the rifle. Plus, this rifle comes with Israeli sling and bayonet. I will ship to C&R holders (you need to provide a copy with your payment) or I will ship to your FFL. Shipping is an additional $35 to the final bidding amount.
